b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p6_parts_per_mb" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Units of Solution Concentration: Parts per Million and Parts per Billion</title>\n        <objref idref="ppm_ppb"/>\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <p>Very low solute concentrations are often expressed using appropriately small units such\n            as <extra><anchor>parts per million (ppm)</anchor><meaning><material><p>ratio of solute-to-solution mass multiplied by 10<sup>6</sup></p></material></meaning></extra> or <extra><anchor>parts per billion (ppb)</anchor><meaning><material><p>ratio of solute-to-solution mass multiplied by 10<sup>9</sup></p></material></meaning></extra>. Like percentage (\xe2\x80\x9cpart per\n            hundred\xe2\x80\x9d) units, ppm and ppb may be defined in terms of masses, volumes, or mixed\n            mass-volume units. There are also ppm and ppb units defined with respect to numbers of\n            atoms and molecules.</p>\n\n        <p>The mass-based definitions of ppm and ppb are given here:</p>\n\n        <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{ppm}\\;=\\;\\frac{\\mathrm{mass}\\;\\mathrm{solute}}{\\mathrm{mass}\\;\\mathrm{solution}}\\;\\times\\;10^6\\;\\mathrm{ppm}\\\\\\\\\\mathrm{ppb}\\;=\\;\\frac{\\mathrm{mass}\\;\\mathrm{solute}}{\\mathrm{mass}\\;\\mathrm{solution}}\\;\\times\\;10^9\\;\\mathrm{ppb}\\end{array}$$</formula>\n\n        <p>Both ppm and ppb are convenient units for reporting the concentrations of pollutants and\n            other trace contaminants in water. Concentrations of these contaminants are typically\n            very low in treated and natural waters, and their levels cannot exceed relatively low\n            concentration thresholds without causing adverse effects on health and wildlife. For\n            example, the EPA has identified the maximum safe level of fluoride ion in tap water to\n            be 4 ppm. Inline water filters are designed to reduce the concentration of fluoride and\n            several other trace-level contaminants in tap water. </p>\n\n        <example>\n            <p>According to the EPA, when the concentration of lead in tap water reaches 15 ppb,\n                certain remedial actions must be taken. What is this concentration in ppm? At this\n                concentration, what mass of lead (\xce\xbcg) would be contained in a typical glass of water\n                (300 mL)?</p>\n\n            <p>The definitions of the ppm and ppb units may be used to convert the given\n                concentration from ppb to ppm. Comparing these two unit definitions shows that ppm\n                is 1000 times greater than ppb (1 ppm = 10<sup>3</sup> ppb). Thus:</p>\n            <formula>$$15\\;\\mathrm{ppb}\\;\\times\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm{ppm}}{10^3\\;\\mathrm{ppb}}\\;=\\;0.015\\;\\mathrm{ppm}$$</formula>\n\n            <p>The definition of the ppb unit may be used to calculate the requested mass if the\n                mass of the solution is provided. However, only the volume of solution (300 mL) is\n                given, so we must use the density to derive the corresponding mass. We can assume\n                the density of tap water to be roughly the same as that of pure water (~1.00 g/mL),\n                since the concentrations of any dissolved substances should not be very large.\n                Rearranging the equation defining the ppb unit and substituting the given quantities\n                yields:</p>\n            \n            <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{ppb}\\;=\\;\\frac{\\mathrm{mass}\\;\\mathrm{solute}}{\\mathrm{mass}\\;\\mathrm{solution}}\\;\\times\\;10^9\\;\\mathrm{ppb}\\\\\\\\\\mathrm{mass}\\;\\mathrm{solute}\\;=\\;\\frac{\\mathrm{ppb}\\;\\times\\;\\mathrm{mass}\\;\\mathrm{solution}}{10^9\\;\\mathrm{ppb}}\\\\\\\\\\mathrm{mass}\\;\\mathrm{solute}\\;=\\;\\frac{15\\;\\mathrm{ppb}\\;\\times\\;300\\;\\mathrm{mL}\\;\\times\\;{\\displaystyle\\frac{1.00\\;\\mathrm g}{\\mathrm{mL}}}}{10^9\\;\\mathrm{ppb}}\\;=\\;4.5\\;\\times\\;10^{-6}\\;\\mathrm g\\end{array}$$</formula>\n            \n            <p>Finally, convert this mass to the requested unit of micrograms:</p>\n            \n            <formula>$$4.5\\;\\times\\;10^{-6}\\;\\mathrm g\\;\\times\\;\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm{\xce\xbcg}}{10^{-6}\\;g}\\;=\\;4.5\\;\\mathrm{\xce\xbcg}$$</formula>\n        </example>\n        \n        <wb:inline idref="ppm_lbd_1" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n        \n        <wb:inline idref="ppm_lbd_2" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n        \n        <wb:inline idref="ppm_digt" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n        \n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n            >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n            href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n            >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n        \n        \n\n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'